parser-core, name-resolver, main.

## Remaining issues found by the checker

### 1. Precedence paren dropping (SEMANTIC BUG, ~30 defs)
The self-hosted CodexEmitter drops necessary parens around binary
sub-expressions:
- `target-pos - (jcc-pos + 6)` → `target-pos - jcc-pos + 6` (WRONG)
- `(n / 16) * 16` → `n / 16 * 16` (same result but fragile)
- Concentrated in x86-64, x86-64helpers, x86-64encoder

Root cause: `emit-expr` in CodexEmitter.codex doesn't track parent operator
precedence, so it never wraps sub-expressions in parens.

### 2. CCE brace escaping (~8 defs in csharp-emitter*)
Stage0 uses `\{` for literal C# braces in string constants.
Stage1 emits `{` without the backslash.
Affects: emit-tco-def, emit-binary, emit-list, emit-match, emit-pattern, etc.

### 3. String literal content diffs (~5 defs)
Multi-line string constants split differently between stages.
`\"\"` vs `\I\n` — CCE escape code mismatch for quote character.
Affects: emit-full-module, emit-module, emit-cce-runtime, emit-builtin.

### 4. Sig mismatches (55 defs, mostly csharp-emitter*)
Many C# emitter functions have different type signatures between stages.
Example: `emit-def : IRDef -> List ArityEntry -> Text` (S0) vs
`emit-def : IRDef -> List Text -> Text` (S1). These are real type system
differences — the self-hosted type checker infers different types.

## Plan for next session

Fix the three body-mismatch categories in order of impact:

1. **Precedence parens** — biggest win, ~30 defs. Add precedence tracking to
   `emit-binary-expr` in `Codex.Codex/Emit/CodexEmitter.codex`. When the
   parent op has higher precedence than the child, wrap in parens.

2. **CCE brace escapes** — ~8 defs. The bare-metal emitter's `escape-text`
   function doesn't handle `{` → `\{` conversion. Fix in
   `Codex.Codex/Emit/CSharpEmitter.codex` (escape-text-loop).

3. **String literal CCE codes** — ~5 defs. The quote-in-string escape uses
   wrong CCE code. Fix in the string literal emitter.

After these fixes, re-run `codex sem-equiv` to measure progress. Target: 100%
body match. Then stage1===stage2 (byte-identical fixed point) becomes testable.

